1
00:00:26,881 --> 00:00:30,093
-Is it around here?
-Yes, we'll be there soon.

2
00:00:30,176 --> 00:00:31,261
Is this it?

3
00:00:32,595 --> 00:00:34,973
All right, let's get our money's worth!

4
00:00:37,892 --> 00:00:39,561
ETHNIC CAFE

5
00:00:47,151 --> 00:00:48,444
This is good stuff.

6
00:00:48,528 --> 00:00:50,113
It's great, isn't it?

7
00:00:53,449 --> 00:00:55,618
Do you not like ethnic food?

8
00:00:58,204 --> 00:01:00,540
Come on, you should have just told me.

9
00:01:00,623 --> 00:01:04,460
Well, every single option
you gave me, Dr. Matsubara,

10
00:01:04,544 --> 00:01:06,379
was ethnic food.

11
00:01:06,462 --> 00:01:08,798
I hate people
who just try and read the room.

12
00:01:08,882 --> 00:01:10,049
Sorry.

13
00:01:10,133 --> 00:01:13,469
But this feeling of the spices
rushing through your whole body

14
00:01:13,553 --> 00:01:15,096
is the absolute best.

15
00:01:16,806 --> 00:01:21,686
Whether a person reads the room or not
won't show up in an autopsy, will it?

16
00:01:22,645 --> 00:01:25,607
If you die, nobody is going to
know your were kind.

17
00:01:26,232 --> 00:01:27,442
I wouldn't want that.

18
00:01:29,903 --> 00:01:30,904
Right…

19
00:01:30,987 --> 00:01:33,448
MOM: YOUR SISTER IS IN TROUBLE

20
00:01:37,076 --> 00:01:39,662
YOUR SISTER IS IN TROUBLE

21
00:01:39,746 --> 00:01:46,878
PARLIAMENT MEMBER TOSHIO AOTA'S
FORBIDDEN AFFAIR: HIS CHIEF SECRETARY!

22
00:02:02,936 --> 00:02:03,770
CONTACTS

23
00:02:03,853 --> 00:02:06,981
SAKI MATSUBARA

24
00:02:14,614 --> 00:02:18,284
OFFICE OF TOSHIO AOTA

25
00:03:11,212 --> 00:03:12,213
Dr. Matsubara?

26
00:03:12,797 --> 00:03:13,631
Yes?

27
00:03:13,715 --> 00:03:15,174
Do you need any help?

28
00:03:15,800 --> 00:03:17,969
No, I'm fine.

29
00:03:20,888 --> 00:03:23,516
Hello, this is Medical Examiner Japan.

30
00:03:25,810 --> 00:03:26,769
What?

31
00:03:27,270 --> 00:03:29,439
The parliament member's office?

32
00:03:30,648 --> 00:03:31,816
Yes.

33
00:03:33,067 --> 00:03:34,110
I understand.

34
00:03:40,199 --> 00:03:41,326
Hello.

35
00:03:41,993 --> 00:03:45,121
The deceased is Toshio Aota,
a lawmaker from the National Party.

36
00:03:45,204 --> 00:03:48,541
When his chief secretary, Saki Matsubara,
visited the office this morning,

37
00:03:48,624 --> 00:03:51,711
he was discovered already hanging.

38
00:03:52,295 --> 00:03:54,922
No suicide note has been found,

39
00:03:55,006 --> 00:03:57,800
but a magazine published an article
about an affair of his.

40
00:03:57,884 --> 00:04:01,262
Furthermore, it was with the person who
first discovered him, Saki Matsubara.

41
00:04:01,346 --> 00:04:04,599
Considering the situation,
the police are viewing it as a suicide.

42
00:04:06,517 --> 00:04:07,352
Wait.

43
00:04:07,435 --> 00:04:09,437
Where's Ms. Dojima?

44
00:04:10,104 --> 00:04:12,940
She was called in by the chief
regarding this case.

45
00:04:15,360 --> 00:04:16,361
Dojima.

46
00:04:16,861 --> 00:04:19,822
Don't look too hard into
the parliament member's death.

47
00:04:20,990 --> 00:04:22,283
You get it, right?

48
00:04:27,246 --> 00:04:29,082
No subcutaneous bleeding.

49
00:04:29,165 --> 00:04:31,292
No facial congestion either.

50
00:04:31,376 --> 00:04:35,380
The stop of circulation
is highly likely due to pressure.

51
00:04:35,963 --> 00:04:37,006
Which means?

52
00:04:37,090 --> 00:04:40,385
There is a possibility
that he was hanged after he died.

53
00:04:41,344 --> 00:04:45,681
I see multiple small,
hole-like wounds on his chest.

54
00:04:48,726 --> 00:04:51,187
The autopsy shows, as expected,

55
00:04:51,270 --> 00:04:56,234
Mr. Aota's cause of death
was not asphyxiation from hanging.

56
00:04:56,317 --> 00:04:59,529
The discoloration on Mr. Aota's
body is concentrated on his back.

57
00:04:59,612 --> 00:05:02,532
If he had died from hanging,

58
00:05:02,615 --> 00:05:06,244
it should have appeared
on his fingers and lower legs.

59
00:05:06,327 --> 00:05:07,370
It doesn't add up.

60
00:05:07,453 --> 00:05:10,415
Does that mean it was murder?

61
00:05:10,498 --> 00:05:15,962
Mr. Aota appears to have suffered
cardiac arrest before he was hanged.

62
00:05:16,045 --> 00:05:20,299
It seems someone used a rope
to hang him several hours after his death.

63
00:05:21,634 --> 00:05:24,595
There are minor scrapes
and bruises on his hands and feet,

64
00:05:24,679 --> 00:05:26,431
but they are all light injuries.

65
00:05:26,514 --> 00:05:27,765
From their location,

66
00:05:27,849 --> 00:05:30,435
they are highly likely
from a fall or a stumble.

67
00:05:30,518 --> 00:05:32,562
Was that fall the cause of death?

68
00:05:34,021 --> 00:05:36,858
There was a mark indicating
a strong impact to the chest.

69
00:05:36,941 --> 00:05:40,903
The shock most likely fractured his ribs,
which punctured his lung.

70
00:05:40,987 --> 00:05:43,197
We also confirmed
bleeding inside the chest,

71
00:05:43,281 --> 00:05:45,908
but nothing that we could say
is the cause of death.

72
00:05:45,992 --> 00:05:50,329
There were also
four small stab wounds on the chest.

73
00:05:50,413 --> 00:05:52,915
Rather than stab wounds from a knife,

74
00:05:52,999 --> 00:05:57,295
it looks more like a mark left by
forcing something sharp into the skin.

75
00:05:58,296 --> 00:06:01,799
There is almost no bleeding
from the wounds, which means

76
00:06:01,883 --> 00:06:04,927
it is highly likely these wounds
were inflicted after death.

77
00:06:05,011 --> 00:06:10,183
Meaning, whoever made those wounds
holds the key to this case?

78
00:06:17,732 --> 00:06:19,483
For now,

79
00:06:19,567 --> 00:06:20,735
it's a mystery.

80
00:06:25,281 --> 00:06:27,533
Apparently, that man Aota,
whom we autopsied today,

81
00:06:27,617 --> 00:06:29,493
was suspected of having an affair.

82
00:06:29,577 --> 00:06:31,871
What? Really?

83
00:06:31,954 --> 00:06:35,416
And it was with his chief secretary
who first found him.

84
00:06:36,083 --> 00:06:38,878
Maybe she killed him over a messy affair.

85
00:06:42,673 --> 00:06:44,300
What do you think, Dr. Matsubara?

86
00:06:49,305 --> 00:06:52,350
That's… my older sister.

87
00:06:53,976 --> 00:06:55,144
-Huh?
-What?

88
00:06:55,228 --> 00:06:57,438
That politician's secretary,
Saki Matsubara.

89
00:06:58,356 --> 00:06:59,815
She's my older sister.

90
00:07:06,906 --> 00:07:10,201
Please let me join the investigation
for this case.

91
00:07:11,494 --> 00:07:13,412
I can't accept this,

92
00:07:13,496 --> 00:07:15,164
so I want to investigate it myself.

93
00:07:17,291 --> 00:07:18,501
Please.

94
00:07:30,304 --> 00:07:31,973
I think

95
00:07:33,057 --> 00:07:34,600
this could be

96
00:07:35,184 --> 00:07:39,605
a piece of a bigger puzzle.

97
00:07:44,860 --> 00:07:46,612
Hello, this is Medical Examiner…

98
00:07:48,948 --> 00:07:49,782
What?

99
00:07:51,909 --> 00:07:52,743
Yes.

100
00:07:52,827 --> 00:07:53,828
That's right.

101
00:07:55,871 --> 00:07:56,956
Yes.

102
00:07:59,208 --> 00:08:00,876
Yes, goodbye.

103
00:08:04,130 --> 00:08:05,590
Is something wrong?

104
00:08:06,591 --> 00:08:12,013
The MHLW told me not to get involved
in the investigation of this case.

105
00:08:38,623 --> 00:08:39,832
I…

106
00:08:41,042 --> 00:08:43,252
was having an affair with Mr. Aota.

107
00:08:46,464 --> 00:08:47,965
We met at my apartment

108
00:08:48,966 --> 00:08:50,968
during the day of the incident.

109
00:08:51,719 --> 00:08:54,388
I seriously can't believe you.
Do you think I'm stupid?

110
00:08:54,472 --> 00:08:59,560
<i>He told me he would divorce his wife,</i>
<i>but he never actually did it.</i>

111
00:08:59,644 --> 00:09:02,980
<i>Recently, we ended up arguing</i>
<i>every time we met.</i>

112
00:09:12,948 --> 00:09:14,200
But I never imagined

113
00:09:15,826 --> 00:09:17,078
he would commit suicide.

114
00:09:17,161 --> 00:09:20,956
We are investigating with
the possibility of murder in mind as well.

115
00:09:22,667 --> 00:09:23,834
Is that so?

116
00:09:24,752 --> 00:09:31,217
Mr. Aota fell from the exterior staircase
of the apartment where you live?

117
00:09:31,801 --> 00:09:32,718
Yes.

118
00:09:34,261 --> 00:09:36,555
May we investigate that?

119
00:09:38,307 --> 00:09:39,183
Go ahead.

120
00:09:41,268 --> 00:09:45,189
No bloodstains or signs of a fall
were found on the apartment stairs.

121
00:09:45,272 --> 00:09:49,110
Aota did not appear
on any of the security cameras either.

122
00:09:49,193 --> 00:09:51,237
The components found in the wound

123
00:09:51,320 --> 00:09:54,323
did not match the concrete components
of the apartment stairs.

124
00:09:57,493 --> 00:10:00,204
None of it adds up.

125
00:10:01,706 --> 00:10:03,499
But that makes no sense.

126
00:10:03,582 --> 00:10:05,376
Why would she come forward

127
00:10:05,459 --> 00:10:07,795
just to lie to us
and seem more suspicious?

128
00:10:08,337 --> 00:10:10,214
There must be a reason.

129
00:10:12,550 --> 00:10:14,260
Dr. Matsubara,

130
00:10:14,343 --> 00:10:16,721
do you have any insights?

131
00:10:20,558 --> 00:10:22,518
She has always been like that.

132
00:10:22,601 --> 00:10:27,773
She just reads the room
and tries to please everyone.

133
00:10:28,607 --> 00:10:31,902
Her special talent was avoiding conflict.

134
00:10:33,988 --> 00:10:35,072
An affair?

135
00:10:36,198 --> 00:10:37,283
Murder?

136
00:10:38,826 --> 00:10:39,994
That's hilarious.

137
00:10:40,077 --> 00:10:41,704
That's a lot of conflict.

138
00:10:48,669 --> 00:10:50,838
She might actually be…

139
00:10:51,839 --> 00:10:53,340
reading the room right now.

140
00:10:55,050 --> 00:11:00,389
So Saki Matsubara knows the truth
that Aota fell somewhere else,

141
00:11:00,473 --> 00:11:07,062
and she is lying
to try and hide another truth?

142
00:11:08,397 --> 00:11:10,691
It is only a possibility.

143
00:11:10,775 --> 00:11:13,068
Did you find anything out
about the stab wounds?

144
00:11:13,152 --> 00:11:15,529
There is something strange
about the entry paths.

145
00:11:15,613 --> 00:11:16,780
Strange?

146
00:11:17,573 --> 00:11:19,283
Out of the four wounds,

147
00:11:19,366 --> 00:11:21,744
three are very shallow,

148
00:11:21,827 --> 00:11:25,331
but the fourth one goes
all the way into the chest cavity.

149
00:11:25,414 --> 00:11:27,208
Furthermore, all the wounds

150
00:11:27,291 --> 00:11:30,544
were deliberately inflicted
along a path that avoids the ribs.

151
00:11:31,378 --> 00:11:32,880
Any trace substances yet?

152
00:11:32,963 --> 00:11:35,090
We should get results soon. I'll check.

153
00:11:46,560 --> 00:11:49,522
PARLIAMENT MEMBER AOTA (50)
FOUND HANGED IN OFFICE

154
00:12:02,743 --> 00:12:04,286
Thank you.

155
00:12:04,370 --> 00:12:05,204
Sure.

156
00:12:05,287 --> 00:12:06,121
Let's eat.

157
00:12:06,205 --> 00:12:07,581
Let's eat.

158
00:12:12,127 --> 00:12:14,421
It's rare to see you working this late.

159
00:12:15,923 --> 00:12:19,718
Apparently, Aota used to work
as a surgeon at Senshu Hospital.

160
00:12:20,261 --> 00:12:23,180
I might find something out,
so I plan to go there tomorrow.

161
00:12:31,855 --> 00:12:35,192
I summarized the policies
Aota was working on.

162
00:12:35,276 --> 00:12:39,280
It looks like he was recently drafting
a bill related to the healthcare system.

163
00:12:40,781 --> 00:12:42,533
Impressive.

164
00:12:43,576 --> 00:12:45,619
This is about all I can do right now.

165
00:12:50,332 --> 00:12:52,126
I really don't like her.

166
00:12:52,751 --> 00:12:53,586
My sister.

167
00:12:57,840 --> 00:13:01,427
She always reads the room
and tries to smooth everything over.

168
00:13:02,928 --> 00:13:05,431
When she’s in trouble,
she takes it all on herself.

169
00:13:07,057 --> 00:13:10,853
She acts tough and says she's fine
even when she isn't.

170
00:13:10,936 --> 00:13:12,479
It's all so annoying.

171
00:13:15,816 --> 00:13:16,734
But…

172
00:13:17,693 --> 00:13:20,946
my sister would never do
anything to hurt another person.

173
00:13:21,780 --> 00:13:23,866
An affair? Murder?

174
00:13:24,408 --> 00:13:26,368
Why would she lie?

175
00:13:38,922 --> 00:13:43,135
That means it's your turn to step in,
Dr. Matsubara.

176
00:13:47,181 --> 00:13:51,352
Living people might tell lies sometimes.

177
00:13:52,561 --> 00:13:55,397
But bodies never do.

178
00:13:58,484 --> 00:14:02,529
The truth is there, I'm sure.

179
00:14:08,619 --> 00:14:10,537
Our food will get cold. Let's eat.

180
00:14:19,213 --> 00:14:20,130
<i>Thank you.</i>

181
00:14:20,214 --> 00:14:21,048
Goodbye.

182
00:14:21,131 --> 00:14:22,007
Goodbye.

183
00:14:23,425 --> 00:14:24,426
Mom.

184
00:14:25,010 --> 00:14:25,886
Are you okay?

185
00:14:27,137 --> 00:14:29,723
Isn't that Mr. Aota's wife?

186
00:14:38,148 --> 00:14:40,693
Is your mother hospitalized?

187
00:14:41,360 --> 00:14:42,319
Yes.

188
00:14:42,403 --> 00:14:45,114
Her lungs have always been a bit weak.

189
00:14:46,240 --> 00:14:47,282
I'm sorry.

190
00:14:47,366 --> 00:14:50,369
We've been going around
asking questions about Mr. Aota.

191
00:14:51,203 --> 00:14:52,830
Did you find out anything?

192
00:14:53,872 --> 00:14:54,832
No.

193
00:14:59,586 --> 00:15:00,587
Hey.

194
00:15:00,671 --> 00:15:02,881
That's the chairman
of the Senshu Group, isn't it?

195
00:15:05,592 --> 00:15:08,303
A charismatic figure
in the medical world who believes

196
00:15:08,387 --> 00:15:09,680
in saving every life.

197
00:15:10,848 --> 00:15:14,018
My husband originally
started working at this hospital

198
00:15:14,101 --> 00:15:16,145
because he admired Chairman Mukai.

199
00:15:16,979 --> 00:15:20,107
Ten years ago, he suddenly
decided to become a politician.

200
00:15:20,190 --> 00:15:23,318
All of Mr. Aota's policies were wonderful.

201
00:15:23,402 --> 00:15:26,780
Or like, they felt created
by a proper human being.

202
00:15:30,617 --> 00:15:31,452
I'm sorry.

203
00:15:35,873 --> 00:15:37,041
On that day,

204
00:15:38,834 --> 00:15:41,253
he told me he would be late,

205
00:15:42,004 --> 00:15:46,592
but would come home early the next day
so we could go out for dinner somewhere.

206
00:15:51,346 --> 00:15:52,306
But…

207
00:15:53,515 --> 00:15:55,809
that day turned out to be his last.

208
00:16:01,356 --> 00:16:02,274
TOSHIO AOTA

209
00:16:02,357 --> 00:16:03,525
May I have a balloon?

210
00:16:03,609 --> 00:16:04,985
-Here you go.
-Thank you.

211
00:16:05,069 --> 00:16:07,154
You're welcome. Bye-bye!

212
00:16:11,450 --> 00:16:13,535
May I have one?

213
00:16:13,619 --> 00:16:14,453
Sure.

214
00:16:14,536 --> 00:16:15,496
Thank you.

215
00:16:15,579 --> 00:16:16,872
Doctor, is that…

216
00:16:17,456 --> 00:16:18,874
The reason balloons float

217
00:16:18,957 --> 00:16:21,877
is because the helium inside it
is lighter than the air around--

218
00:16:25,172 --> 00:16:26,298
It's okay.

219
00:16:26,965 --> 00:16:27,800
Take this one.

220
00:16:36,558 --> 00:16:37,518
It's okay.

221
00:16:37,601 --> 00:16:38,811
Have this one.

222
00:16:41,146 --> 00:16:42,731
Thank you very much.

223
00:16:42,815 --> 00:16:44,775
Thank you!

224
00:16:44,858 --> 00:16:45,984
Let's go.

225
00:16:52,825 --> 00:16:54,118
Excuse me.

226
00:16:54,201 --> 00:16:55,285
One more?

227
00:16:56,954 --> 00:16:58,205
One more, please.

228
00:16:58,288 --> 00:16:59,206
Oh, sure.

229
00:16:59,289 --> 00:17:00,541
Thank you, sorry.

230
00:17:00,624 --> 00:17:01,542
Thank you.

231
00:17:04,128 --> 00:17:05,212
Sorry.

232
00:17:12,511 --> 00:17:14,972
When you listen
to the stories of the living,

233
00:17:15,514 --> 00:17:18,350
the truth becomes harder to know.

234
00:17:21,979 --> 00:17:23,522
Dr. Masumi.

235
00:17:23,605 --> 00:17:26,733
Do you ever read the room?

236
00:17:30,237 --> 00:17:34,324
The human brain contains nerve cells
called mirror neurons.

237
00:17:34,408 --> 00:17:37,703
These are brain cells that react
to actions of others

238
00:17:37,786 --> 00:17:40,205
by mirroring what we observe.

239
00:17:41,039 --> 00:17:42,499
Because of this function,

240
00:17:42,583 --> 00:17:46,128
we are naturally wired to empathize
with the words and actions of others.

241
00:17:52,009 --> 00:17:52,926
What is it?

242
00:17:54,678 --> 00:17:56,263
I just read the room.

243
00:17:57,890 --> 00:17:59,057
So you can read it?

244
00:17:59,641 --> 00:18:01,685
It's simply the function of nerve cells.

245
00:18:02,686 --> 00:18:04,062
Is that how it works?

246
00:18:13,363 --> 00:18:15,699
I don't think it's a bad thing.

247
00:18:18,827 --> 00:18:23,957
Reading the room
is an innate ability humans possess.

248
00:18:24,041 --> 00:18:26,668
It is one of our tools for survival.

249
00:18:49,566 --> 00:18:51,401
Take a seat wherever.

250
00:18:57,199 --> 00:18:59,618
You didn't engage in an affair, right?

251
00:19:00,494 --> 00:19:02,746
You read the weekly magazines, didn't you?

252
00:19:02,829 --> 00:19:04,039
They're lying.

253
00:19:04,122 --> 00:19:05,332
They're not.

254
00:19:05,874 --> 00:19:06,708
Why?

255
00:19:10,003 --> 00:19:11,463
Answer my question.

256
00:19:12,839 --> 00:19:14,800
There is no particular reason.

257
00:19:14,883 --> 00:19:16,885
I just fell in love with him, that's all.

258
00:19:16,969 --> 00:19:19,096
But what you said
about the stairs was a lie.

259
00:19:25,102 --> 00:19:26,395
You didn't kill him, right?

260
00:19:28,814 --> 00:19:29,940
Hey.

261
00:19:30,023 --> 00:19:31,566
What are you trying to protect?

262
00:19:31,650 --> 00:19:33,318
Is it really that important to you?

263
00:19:33,402 --> 00:19:35,028
Is it worth more than your own life?

264
00:19:35,112 --> 00:19:36,071
Shut up!

265
00:19:37,823 --> 00:19:40,409
Don't assume everyone
can live their life like you do.

266
00:19:41,910 --> 00:19:42,828
What?

267
00:19:43,996 --> 00:19:45,372
What does that mean?

268
00:19:46,164 --> 00:19:48,542
Suzune, you've always been this way.

269
00:19:48,625 --> 00:19:51,461
You think speaking the truth
makes you entirely right.

270
00:19:52,754 --> 00:19:56,008
I have spent my whole life living
in a world that isn't quite so simple.

271
00:19:58,218 --> 00:20:01,722
A world like that
is completely meaningless.

272
00:20:06,268 --> 00:20:07,686
Just leave.

273
00:20:14,401 --> 00:20:15,235
Fine.

274
00:20:16,695 --> 00:20:18,697
But answer me just one last thing.

275
00:20:19,281 --> 00:20:20,198
What?

276
00:20:20,699 --> 00:20:24,161
Did you truly love Aota?

277
00:20:24,244 --> 00:20:25,746
What kind of question is that?

278
00:20:26,330 --> 00:20:29,958
Did you genuinely intend
to build a life together with Aota?

279
00:20:38,675 --> 00:20:39,843
Yes, I did.

280
00:20:42,846 --> 00:20:43,847
See?

281
00:20:44,598 --> 00:20:45,557
Are we done now?

282
00:20:46,475 --> 00:20:47,559
Leave.

283
00:20:58,779 --> 00:21:03,075
These are the chemical components
from Aota's clothing and nasal cavity.

284
00:21:04,242 --> 00:21:07,996
The amount of volatile sulfur compounds
is exceptionally high.

285
00:21:08,497 --> 00:21:09,539
Yes.

286
00:21:09,623 --> 00:21:11,416
I can't quite figure out this part.

287
00:21:11,500 --> 00:21:14,669
We also recovered traces
of phthalocyanine pigments,

288
00:21:14,753 --> 00:21:17,714
glycerol, emulsifiers, and fragrance
from the stab wounds.

289
00:21:17,798 --> 00:21:19,716
Phthalocyanine is a pigment, isn't it?

290
00:21:19,800 --> 00:21:21,551
The kind used in paints and inks.

291
00:21:21,635 --> 00:21:24,137
Glycerol is commonly used
as a solvent in ink as well.

292
00:21:24,221 --> 00:21:26,932
Emulsifiers and fragrances
point toward cosmetics.

293
00:21:32,562 --> 00:21:33,939
It's a mystery.

294
00:21:36,858 --> 00:21:38,443
I need to look into something.

295
00:21:40,195 --> 00:21:41,279
What?

296
00:21:42,614 --> 00:21:46,410
There might be a piece of the puzzle
we've missed.

297
00:21:53,875 --> 00:21:55,419
CHEMICAL COMPOUNDS

298
00:22:15,105 --> 00:22:17,941
This… might be the secret spice.

299
00:22:19,568 --> 00:22:21,486
The secret spice?

300
00:22:21,570 --> 00:22:23,029
Asafoetida.

301
00:22:23,113 --> 00:22:25,198
Otherwise known as the secret spice.

302
00:22:26,199 --> 00:22:27,826
It is native to South Africa

303
00:22:27,909 --> 00:22:31,413
and has a vey strong odor,
much like garlic or durian.

304
00:22:35,375 --> 00:22:37,460
The chemical composition is a close match.

305
00:22:37,544 --> 00:22:40,338
When heated in oil,
it volatilizes quickly,

306
00:22:40,422 --> 00:22:43,717
which explains how microparticles
could adhere to someone.

307
00:22:43,800 --> 00:22:46,136
Incredible, Dr. Matsubara!

308
00:22:46,219 --> 00:22:47,470
Ethnic maniac!

309
00:22:48,889 --> 00:22:52,475
This feeling of the spices
rushing through your whole body

310
00:22:52,559 --> 00:22:54,352
<i>is the absolute best.</i>

311
00:22:54,853 --> 00:22:55,937
SECRET SPICE CURRY

312
00:22:57,731 --> 00:22:59,107
I need to go verify this.

313
00:22:59,691 --> 00:23:00,525
What?

314
00:23:01,109 --> 00:23:03,278
Don't tell me you're leaving too?

315
00:23:03,862 --> 00:23:07,490
There might be a piece of the puzzle
we've missed.

316
00:23:07,991 --> 00:23:10,911
We are indeed using it
in our current special menu, but…

317
00:23:11,494 --> 00:23:15,040
Did you happen to hear anything heavy
falling nearby on that day?

318
00:23:15,123 --> 00:23:17,500
Oh, I'm not sure…

319
00:23:42,234 --> 00:23:44,110
EMERGENCY LADDER

320
00:24:13,431 --> 00:24:17,018
That day, Aota fell down the stairs
at the Sanyo Hotel.

321
00:24:17,102 --> 00:24:19,604
I believe he took a heavy hit
to his chest after falling.

322
00:24:19,688 --> 00:24:21,147
If that's the case,

323
00:24:21,231 --> 00:24:23,024
then he really did die from a fall, right?

324
00:24:23,108 --> 00:24:26,236
But we still don't understand
the mystery of the stab wound.

325
00:24:36,371 --> 00:24:39,624
<i>Like a mark left by forcing</i>
<i>something sharp into the skin.</i>

326
00:24:39,708 --> 00:24:41,293
I was having an affair with Toshio Aota.

327
00:24:41,376 --> 00:24:43,461
<i>I believe he took a heavy hit</i>
<i>to his chest after falling.</i>

328
00:24:43,545 --> 00:24:46,631
<i>We also recovered traces of phthalocyanine</i>
<i>pigments from the stab wounds.</i>

329
00:24:46,715 --> 00:24:48,425
<i>The kind used in paints and inks.</i>

330
00:24:48,508 --> 00:24:50,343
Her lungs have always been a bit weak.

331
00:24:50,427 --> 00:24:52,012
<i>She just reads the room…</i>

332
00:25:00,103 --> 00:25:01,479
The pieces might be…

333
00:25:02,522 --> 00:25:04,065
coming together.

334
00:25:10,905 --> 00:25:11,740
First,

335
00:25:11,823 --> 00:25:13,908
regarding Aota's cause of death,

336
00:25:14,492 --> 00:25:16,453
a certain hypothesis has been formed.

337
00:25:17,662 --> 00:25:22,042
Traces of a rare spice called asafoetida
have been detected

338
00:25:22,125 --> 00:25:25,754
on the clothing Aota wore
and in his nasal cavity.

339
00:25:26,629 --> 00:25:28,298
On the day Aota died,

340
00:25:28,381 --> 00:25:32,344
a dish using this spice
was being served at the Sanyo Hotel.

341
00:25:32,427 --> 00:25:35,138
And, Aota's fingerprints and bloodstains

342
00:25:35,221 --> 00:25:37,640
were detected
on the hotel's external stairs.

343
00:25:38,391 --> 00:25:39,642
It is likely that,

344
00:25:39,726 --> 00:25:42,812
somehow, Aota fell from
these stairs and hit his chest hard,

345
00:25:42,896 --> 00:25:45,774
fracturing his ribs,
causing a hole to open in his lungs.

346
00:25:46,858 --> 00:25:50,779
When a hole opens in the lung,
air leaks into the chest cavity,

347
00:25:50,862 --> 00:25:52,947
putting pressure on the lung and heart.

348
00:25:53,031 --> 00:25:56,242
This condition is called
a tension pneumothorax.

349
00:25:56,326 --> 00:25:58,912
Judging from
the circumstances of the fall,

350
00:25:58,995 --> 00:26:02,290
it would not be surprising if Aota
had developed tension pneumothorax.

351
00:26:02,374 --> 00:26:05,752
However, during the autopsy,
we found no air to be trapped there.

352
00:26:05,835 --> 00:26:10,215
A tension pneumothorax
is a life-threatening, critical condition.

353
00:26:10,298 --> 00:26:11,758
As an emergency measure,

354
00:26:11,841 --> 00:26:15,887
you must puncture the chest cavity,
before it becomes fatal.

355
00:26:17,889 --> 00:26:18,973
What is it?

356
00:26:20,642 --> 00:26:23,436
Could you stab that into the chest cavity?

357
00:26:23,937 --> 00:26:25,146
The chest cavity?

358
00:26:26,106 --> 00:26:28,358
As a rough guide, it's around here.

359
00:26:28,441 --> 00:26:31,152
To be exact, it's between the ribs.

360
00:26:32,028 --> 00:26:33,988
No, no way I could do that.

361
00:26:45,458 --> 00:26:46,459
Could you do it?

362
00:26:53,174 --> 00:26:57,804
Traces of what is believed to be
ink pigments were detected in the wounds.

363
00:26:57,887 --> 00:26:59,389
And in his office,

364
00:26:59,472 --> 00:27:03,977
parts of a ballpoint pen with ink
components that match were found.

365
00:27:04,060 --> 00:27:05,437
If someone,

366
00:27:05,520 --> 00:27:07,313
as a life-saving measure for Aota,

367
00:27:07,397 --> 00:27:09,566
who was suffering
from a tension pneumothorax,

368
00:27:09,649 --> 00:27:11,776
had stabbed a ballpoint pen into him,

369
00:27:11,860 --> 00:27:16,281
and if that procedure
had relieved the tension pneumothorax,

370
00:27:16,906 --> 00:27:19,367
it would be difficult
to notice it during an autopsy.

371
00:27:25,248 --> 00:27:29,752
Aota's chest wound
was not a trace of an attempt to kill him.

372
00:27:29,836 --> 00:27:36,176
I believe it is a sign of an effort
to save his life.

373
00:27:43,516 --> 00:27:45,101
For Mr. Aota's sake as well,

374
00:27:46,311 --> 00:27:47,896
won't you please

375
00:27:49,063 --> 00:27:50,940
tell us the truth?

376
00:28:05,205 --> 00:28:06,372
I'm sorry.

377
00:28:11,461 --> 00:28:12,712
I'm sorry.

378
00:28:13,713 --> 00:28:16,549
<i>A long time ago,</i>
<i>when I was walking with my mother…</i>

379
00:28:16,633 --> 00:28:17,842
Mom, what's wrong?

380
00:28:17,926 --> 00:28:21,679
<i>She suddenly clutched her chest</i>
<i>and collapsed.</i>

381
00:28:21,763 --> 00:28:22,972
Are you okay?

382
00:28:23,056 --> 00:28:24,599
Mom, are you okay?

383
00:28:25,892 --> 00:28:27,143
I'm a doctor.

384
00:28:35,902 --> 00:28:38,363
She is experiencing
a tension pneumothorax.

385
00:28:38,446 --> 00:28:40,073
I have performed emergency first aid.

386
00:28:40,156 --> 00:28:42,700
I'm sorry, but please rest assured.

387
00:28:44,536 --> 00:28:46,704
-Thank you so much.
-Call an ambulance.

388
00:28:47,872 --> 00:28:52,710
We had been married
and together for so many years…

389
00:28:54,546 --> 00:28:57,090
and I thought I knew everything about him.

390
00:28:58,424 --> 00:28:59,801
But lately,

391
00:29:00,385 --> 00:29:02,804
he seemed to be hiding something.

392
00:29:05,014 --> 00:29:07,267
That's why, on that day,

393
00:29:07,934 --> 00:29:11,312
<i>I really suspected</i>
<i>he was having an affair.</i>

394
00:29:16,484 --> 00:29:17,527
Mr. Kakei!

395
00:29:22,615 --> 00:29:24,158
Do you have a moment?

396
00:29:24,659 --> 00:29:25,952
Not in here.

397
00:29:26,035 --> 00:29:27,453
Let's go somewhere else.

398
00:29:34,919 --> 00:29:37,672
Please retract that article.

399
00:29:39,090 --> 00:29:41,885
It's because you guys
are sneaking around snooping.

400
00:29:43,761 --> 00:29:45,889
Bribery is a crime.

401
00:29:50,602 --> 00:29:54,898
You're an adult,
so read the room a little bit more.

402
00:29:55,940 --> 00:29:57,025
Besides,

403
00:29:57,734 --> 00:29:59,944
an evil that can bring change

404
00:30:00,778 --> 00:30:04,198
is far better than justice
that can't change anything, isn't it?

405
00:30:13,750 --> 00:30:14,959
Mr. Aota!

406
00:30:16,294 --> 00:30:17,420
Follow him!

407
00:30:19,005 --> 00:30:20,006
Okay!

408
00:30:25,803 --> 00:30:26,804
Dear!

409
00:30:26,888 --> 00:30:28,014
Are you all right?

410
00:30:28,097 --> 00:30:29,223
Kaede?

411
00:30:29,724 --> 00:30:30,934
OFFICE OF TOSHIO AOTA

412
00:30:31,017 --> 00:30:32,435
<i>Explain to me what happened.</i>

413
00:30:34,354 --> 00:30:35,563
I'm sorry.

414
00:30:37,482 --> 00:30:38,483
Let's separate.

415
00:30:39,067 --> 00:30:39,901
What?

416
00:30:39,984 --> 00:30:41,986
It's better if we aren't together.

417
00:30:43,029 --> 00:30:45,239
Kaede, pretend you didn't know anything.

418
00:30:46,658 --> 00:30:47,992
Live a normal life.

419
00:30:49,285 --> 00:30:50,828
What are you saying?

420
00:30:52,330 --> 00:30:53,539
I don't understand!

421
00:31:00,505 --> 00:31:01,631
Dear?

422
00:31:03,967 --> 00:31:05,259
Dear!

423
00:31:08,179 --> 00:31:09,263
Dear!

424
00:31:09,847 --> 00:31:11,224
Dear!

425
00:31:11,307 --> 00:31:12,350
Dear!

426
00:31:12,433 --> 00:31:14,644
Dear! Are you okay? What's wrong?

427
00:31:17,271 --> 00:31:18,648
What?

428
00:31:37,792 --> 00:31:39,168
Dear!

429
00:31:39,252 --> 00:31:40,503
It's not working!

430
00:31:43,006 --> 00:31:45,216
Dear! Don't go!

431
00:32:01,024 --> 00:32:02,984
Dear?

432
00:32:05,486 --> 00:32:06,654
Dear…

433
00:32:07,405 --> 00:32:08,656
Why?

434
00:32:10,199 --> 00:32:11,909
Dear!

435
00:32:19,834 --> 00:32:21,127
I…

436
00:32:22,336 --> 00:32:24,589
killed my husband, didn't I?

437
00:32:25,590 --> 00:32:27,675
Out of the four stab wounds,

438
00:32:28,384 --> 00:32:31,929
one of them successfully punctured
his chest cavity

439
00:32:32,013 --> 00:32:34,432
and allowed air to escape.

440
00:32:36,142 --> 00:32:37,185
However,

441
00:32:37,894 --> 00:32:39,854
by that point,

442
00:32:40,772 --> 00:32:42,648
your husband had already passed.

443
00:32:47,737 --> 00:32:49,072
The traces…

444
00:32:50,948 --> 00:32:52,658
of your attempts to save him…

445
00:32:54,744 --> 00:32:56,579
told us the truth.

446
00:33:00,750 --> 00:33:03,127
I believe your husband

447
00:33:04,754 --> 00:33:06,589
was trying his best

448
00:33:06,672 --> 00:33:09,509
to stay alive as long as he could
for your sake.

449
00:33:28,111 --> 00:33:31,322
I never had an affair with him.

450
00:33:33,533 --> 00:33:34,784
Mr. Aota…

451
00:33:38,079 --> 00:33:39,330
Mr. Aota…

452
00:33:43,042 --> 00:33:47,088
was trying to expose
the bribery between Mr. Kakei

453
00:33:48,965 --> 00:33:51,050
and the Senshu Group.

454
00:33:55,763 --> 00:33:57,974
It was about a month ago

455
00:33:58,933 --> 00:34:02,311
when Mr. Aota realized that Chairman Mukai
of the Senshu Group

456
00:34:03,062 --> 00:34:05,189
<i>was giving bribes to Kakei.</i>

457
00:34:05,273 --> 00:34:06,691
Why would you bribe him?

458
00:34:06,774 --> 00:34:12,155
To expand this hospital
and save as many lives as possible.

459
00:34:12,697 --> 00:34:15,158
I will do whatever it takes
for that cause.

460
00:34:17,493 --> 00:34:20,413
Doing that, the future of
Japanese healthcare will be--

461
00:34:20,496 --> 00:34:25,209
I have seen countless hospitals collapse
because of that kind of idealistic talk.

462
00:34:27,962 --> 00:34:32,550
Saving as many lives
as possible through politics…

463
00:34:34,719 --> 00:34:36,971
That may just be idealistic talk.

464
00:34:39,599 --> 00:34:43,186
I might drag you into this as well.

465
00:34:43,936 --> 00:34:45,354
If you want out, do it now.

466
00:34:50,151 --> 00:34:52,653
I will give it some thought.

467
00:34:57,033 --> 00:34:58,951
The bribes were always in cash.

468
00:35:00,369 --> 00:35:01,329
And that day,

469
00:35:01,829 --> 00:35:07,293
we tracked down their location
and were about to secure the evidence,

470
00:35:08,211 --> 00:35:11,130
but Kakei caught wind of our movements.

471
00:35:11,214 --> 00:35:12,381
Follow him!

472
00:35:13,049 --> 00:35:14,008
Okay!

473
00:35:16,093 --> 00:35:17,261
Mr. Kakei!

474
00:35:20,223 --> 00:35:21,307
What?

475
00:35:24,560 --> 00:35:25,728
I…

476
00:35:28,439 --> 00:35:31,609
I believe the role of politics
is to create a world

477
00:35:33,110 --> 00:35:35,112
where we can call what is right, right.

478
00:35:49,210 --> 00:35:50,962
Aota's bill

479
00:35:52,213 --> 00:35:54,757
is going through
the internal procedures, right?

480
00:35:55,925 --> 00:35:57,760
You want it to pass, don't you?

481
00:36:00,221 --> 00:36:02,014
You were being threatened?

482
00:36:03,891 --> 00:36:05,518
Neither I nor Kakei

483
00:36:07,311 --> 00:36:10,273
knew the truth behind Mr. Aota's death.

484
00:36:14,485 --> 00:36:15,653
So,

485
00:36:17,196 --> 00:36:20,116
when Kakei found out that Mr. Aota
was going to be autopsied,

486
00:36:21,575 --> 00:36:23,077
he panicked…

487
00:36:25,955 --> 00:36:26,872
and he…

488
00:36:26,956 --> 00:36:28,916
You didn't have to…

489
00:36:33,129 --> 00:36:34,630
That bill…

490
00:36:37,341 --> 00:36:39,885
contained all of Mr. Aota's hopes.

491
00:36:44,515 --> 00:36:46,392
I don't understand.

492
00:36:48,060 --> 00:36:52,732
I don't understand why you've kept quiet
this whole time, Kaede.

493
00:36:53,774 --> 00:36:57,278
After all, you weren't the one
who fabricated the evidence, right?

494
00:36:58,029 --> 00:37:00,448
You're still hiding something, aren't you?

495
00:37:04,702 --> 00:37:06,078
A prosecutor came.

496
00:37:06,954 --> 00:37:08,039
A prosecutor?

497
00:37:14,587 --> 00:37:17,882
<i>He told me that if he were transported</i>
<i>to the hospital as he was,</i>

498
00:37:18,549 --> 00:37:21,594
<i>it would be written off</i>
<i>as a disease or sudden death.</i>

499
00:37:23,220 --> 00:37:26,182
He said everything
would be covered up by Kakei.

500
00:37:28,726 --> 00:37:31,312
The corruption my husband tried to expose,

501
00:37:32,229 --> 00:37:33,981
and the hopes he had in politics,

502
00:37:34,065 --> 00:37:36,692
would all be wiped away
as if they never happened.

503
00:37:38,736 --> 00:37:41,238
I absolutely could not allow that.

504
00:37:43,991 --> 00:37:46,369
So, I decided to wager everything on this.

505
00:37:47,828 --> 00:37:48,871
But…

506
00:37:50,581 --> 00:37:53,501
I've been worried this entire time
if it was the right thing to do.

507
00:37:55,211 --> 00:38:00,049
The next day, when the police contacted me
saying they found him hanging,

508
00:38:01,675 --> 00:38:04,220
it completely stopped making sense to me.

509
00:38:29,954 --> 00:38:32,456
Oh, it's very red.

510
00:38:32,540 --> 00:38:33,833
Let's see.

511
00:38:33,916 --> 00:38:34,750
There.

512
00:38:36,460 --> 00:38:38,087
Oh, that was shocking.

513
00:38:38,170 --> 00:38:39,964
Sorry, that's not why I'm here.

514
00:38:40,047 --> 00:38:42,341
I didn't do that on purpose, sorry.

515
00:38:42,425 --> 00:38:44,218
Oh, man.

516
00:38:45,302 --> 00:38:46,470
Mizusawa.

517
00:38:47,179 --> 00:38:48,305
That's you, right?

518
00:38:48,389 --> 00:38:50,891
What was the conclusion
on Aota's cause of death?

519
00:38:52,810 --> 00:38:54,812
It's believed to be tension pneumothorax

520
00:38:54,895 --> 00:38:57,022
resulting from a fall down the stairs.

521
00:38:57,106 --> 00:39:00,401
Is there a possibility that someone
intentionally pushed him down?

522
00:39:01,152 --> 00:39:04,238
None of the wounds
or bruises left on Mr. Aota's body

523
00:39:04,321 --> 00:39:07,074
provides clear proof of homicidal intent.

524
00:39:07,158 --> 00:39:10,411
Furthermore, considering their statements,
it doesn't add up.

525
00:39:11,120 --> 00:39:12,371
It doesn't add up, huh?

526
00:39:12,455 --> 00:39:13,539
Yes.

527
00:39:13,622 --> 00:39:14,665
It doesn't add up.

528
00:39:14,748 --> 00:39:19,211
It doesn't add up, which means
it was bribery after all.

529
00:39:19,295 --> 00:39:20,463
Oops.

530
00:39:20,546 --> 00:39:22,465
Tails, that makes sense.

531
00:39:22,548 --> 00:39:25,301
Excuse me, but who are you?

532
00:39:26,886 --> 00:39:28,053
I'm Ota.

533
00:39:28,637 --> 00:39:30,389
From the Public Prosecutors Office.

534
00:39:32,224 --> 00:39:33,601
A prosecutor?

535
00:39:33,684 --> 00:39:36,520
By the way,
I heard you went to see Dr. Kujo?

536
00:39:37,146 --> 00:39:38,147
How did it go?

537
00:39:38,230 --> 00:39:40,065
Were you able to speak with him?

538
00:39:43,402 --> 00:39:44,445
Well?

539
00:39:47,406 --> 00:39:48,741
You didn't?

540
00:39:48,824 --> 00:39:49,867
Oh, listen.

541
00:39:49,950 --> 00:39:54,955
Bribery paid in cash makes it
quite difficult to secure evidence.

542
00:39:55,873 --> 00:39:59,668
However, it has been confirmed
that Chairman Mukai

543
00:39:59,752 --> 00:40:01,378
was at the hotel that day.

544
00:40:01,921 --> 00:40:05,633
Therefore, if we have
Mr. Aota's autopsy results

545
00:40:06,592 --> 00:40:08,719
and the testimony of both individuals,

546
00:40:09,220 --> 00:40:12,640
it will serve as major leverage
to pursue Kakei.

547
00:40:12,723 --> 00:40:14,433
Your methods are foul.

548
00:40:15,351 --> 00:40:18,896
Our objective is also
to uncover the truth.

549
00:40:18,979 --> 00:40:21,857
An unnatural death
must always be autopsied.

550
00:40:21,941 --> 00:40:25,986
You just used the MEJ system
to bring down a powerful politician.

551
00:40:26,654 --> 00:40:27,488
Used?

552
00:40:27,571 --> 00:40:29,448
Fabricating a suicide by hanging

553
00:40:29,532 --> 00:40:32,243
constitutes the crimes
of damaging and abandoning a corpse.

554
00:40:34,578 --> 00:40:35,871
Is that so?

555
00:40:37,081 --> 00:40:38,165
What?

556
00:40:41,126 --> 00:40:42,419
Please leave.

557
00:40:45,381 --> 00:40:48,968
This is a place
to listen to the voices of the deceased

558
00:40:49,051 --> 00:40:51,387
and uncover the truth.

559
00:40:53,639 --> 00:40:58,310
It is a place to learn
what they loved and who loved them.

560
00:40:59,353 --> 00:41:02,022
It's not for you to bring in
your self-serving narratives!

561
00:41:19,623 --> 00:41:21,041
Didn't you hear her?

562
00:41:21,792 --> 00:41:22,960
Please leave.

563
00:41:30,426 --> 00:41:32,553
Heads or tails? Pick.

564
00:41:39,518 --> 00:41:40,519
What?

565
00:41:44,773 --> 00:41:47,526
See you around.

566
00:42:02,416 --> 00:42:04,960
I think I went a bit too far.

567
00:42:08,297 --> 00:42:11,008
You can just be scolded for it later.

568
00:42:12,426 --> 00:42:13,677
Don't worry about it.

569
00:42:46,377 --> 00:42:53,050
I still want… to live in a world
where I can call what is right, right.

570
00:42:55,344 --> 00:42:56,178
Yeah.

571
00:42:58,639 --> 00:43:01,392
You can't let people
you don't even believe are right

572
00:43:01,892 --> 00:43:03,936
run your life.

573
00:43:10,693 --> 00:43:12,569
Reading the room

574
00:43:13,237 --> 00:43:15,698
is different from
letting yourself be used.

575
00:43:20,828 --> 00:43:21,954
You're right.

576
00:43:31,422 --> 00:43:34,174
So Kakei ended up
not being prosecuted after all, huh?

577
00:43:34,842 --> 00:43:37,428
They say he claims
his secretary did everything.

578
00:43:38,512 --> 00:43:40,931
In the end, nothing changes, huh?

579
00:43:43,058 --> 00:43:45,018
It looks like the bill Mr. Aota drafted

580
00:43:46,186 --> 00:43:48,230
was properly submitted.

581
00:43:49,314 --> 00:43:51,942
The younger politicians
carried on his vision.

582
00:43:52,025 --> 00:43:53,444
It's true!

583
00:43:54,194 --> 00:43:56,530
If you seriously want to change things,

584
00:43:56,613 --> 00:43:58,073
they will change.

585
00:43:59,408 --> 00:44:01,201
I want to believe that.

586
00:44:05,497 --> 00:44:07,541
All right, let's work.

587
00:44:23,098 --> 00:44:25,976
Subtitle translation by: Maslin F.

